body:
Given the [following code](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=693b0889d179397e150d58a4fa2fe20f):

```rust
trait Graph {
    type NodeData;
    
    fn add_node(&mut self, node_data: Self::NodeData);
}

struct GraphStruct<T> {
    t: Option<T>,
}

impl<T> Graph for GraphStruct<T> {
    type NodeData = T;
    
    fn add_node(&mut self, node_data: Self::NodeData) {
        self.t = Some(node_data);
    }
}

fn create_graph<T: 'static>() -> impl Graph<NodeData = T> {
    GraphStruct {t: None}
}

fn main() {
    let vector = Vec::new();
    let mut graph = create_graph::<&[u8]>();
    graph.add_node(&vector[..]);
}
```

The current output is:

```
   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0597]: `vector` does not live long enough
  --> src/main.rs:26:21
   |
26 |     graph.add_node(&vector[..]);
   |     ----------------^^^^^^-----
   |     |               |
   |     |               borrowed value does not live long enough
   |     argument requires that `vector` is borrowed for `'static`
27 | }
   | - `vector` dropped here while still borrowed

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0597`.
error: could not compile `playground` due to previous error
```

Ideally the output should explain where the `'static` bound comes from.
It should point to the method `create_graph` that adds the `'static` bound to the type parameter `Graph::NodeData`.

It took me more than an hour to make this connection in a larger set of crates.

The output is the same for stable, beta and nightly on edition 2018.
